title: Resource minister invited to US as Trump turns to Australia for rare earths
description: United States President Donald Trump will look to Australia as an alternative to China’s metal supply.  Australia’s supply of 17 metals, known as “rare earths”, will be the subject of talks with the United States.  The metals are used in products including electric vehicles and missiles.  Resources Minister Madeleine King has been invited to a US allies meeting with Secretary of State Marco Rubio.

title: Trump threatens to sue Epstein estate and Michael Wolff, asserts new files dump absolves him
description: US President Donald Trump has threatened to sue the Jeffrey Epstein estate and author Michael Wolff following the latest file dump.  While speaking to reporters on Air Force One, President Trump also asserted that the latest Epstein file release absolves him.  “I didn't see it myself, but I was told by some very important people that not only does it absolve me, it's the opposite of what people were hoping, you know, the radical left, that Wolff who is a third rate writer, was conspiring with Jeffrey Epstein to hurt me, politically or otherwise, and that came through loud and clear. So we'll probably sue Wolff on that,” Trump said.  A reporter followed up on Trump’s remark, asking the president again if he was “going to sue the Epstein estate”.  “I guess so, because he was conspiring with Wolff to do harm to me politically. That's not a friend,” Trump added.

title: 'F***ing posers': Bill Maher takes down lefty celebrity activists with savage roast
description: ‘Real Time’ host Bill Maher has savagely ripped into celebrities and their “activism” during a brutal monologue.  In an eight-minute editorial, Maher unloaded on lefty celebrities, expressing that they are “handing elections” to the Republican Party.  Maher expressed that out of touch celebrity’s activism was negative for the Democratic Party, and they were “making independents vote Republican”.  “Congratulations for raising awareness, the awareness you really care about, which is how wonderful you are,” Maher said.

title: King Charles ‘won’t provide accommodation for Andrew’, according to top royal insider
description: TalkTV host Mark Dolan discusses Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor’s situation which has gotten worse since the release of the latest batch of files relating to Jeffrey Epstein.  “I’ve just spoken on my TalkTV show to Andrew Lownie – now this is the guy that wrote the book ‘Entitled’, which was the beginning of the end for Andrew,” Mr Dolan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “And Andrew told me a couple of interesting things. He told me that he thinks King Charles will not provide accommodation for Andrew; that the former Duke of York is going to have to go to the Middle East and have a rich sheikh look after him.  “This is a major move.”

title: Olympic-themed Venice Carnival kicks off two-week celebrations
description: Annual Carnival celebrations in Venice have kicked off with a nod to another big event about to start in Italy.  The theme is ‘Olympus - back to the origins of the games’ in honour of the Winter Olympics starting later this week.  Embracing the lagoons the city is famous for, crowds gathered on the Rialto Bridge to watch the nearly two-week celebration begin.

title: One Nation defections rumoured as the Coalition drama continues to unfold
description: One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson and One Nation MP Barnaby Joyce are flagging a big announcement for Tuesday.  Two names are currently being thrown about for a potential defection to the One Nation Party, including former South Australian Senator Cory Bernardi and Liberal Senator Alex Antic.  Mr Bernardi recently stated he is “so happy” that One Nation’s time has come.

title: ‘Going to end badly’: Albanese likens Coalition to ‘Married at First Sight’ reality show
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has likened the Coalition to the reality television show Married at First Sight.  “The other side, we will allow them to engage in their bizarre behaviour,” Mr Albanese said.  “I note that Married at First Sight begins tonight, and it’s a bit like that with the relationships on the other side, you know they’re going to end badly.  “That’s what we are seeing played out in real time.”

title: UK in ‘political chaos’ amid economic struggles
description: TalkTV host Mark Dolan claims the UK is in “political chaos” amid increasing crime and a struggling economy.  “We’ve got political chaos in the UK at the moment,” Mr Dolan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “We’ve got a tanking economy, eyewatering inflation, massive debt, crime on the streets, and the ... monarchy is there to provide stability – good luck with that.”

title: ‘Largest release we’ve seen’: More high-profile names revealed in Epstein saga
description: CNN Correspondent Julia Benbrook discusses the newly released Epstein files as over three million pages have been made public.  “This is the largest release that we’ve seen, more than three million pages of materials and among those, more than 182,000 photos and videos,” Ms Benbrook told Sky News Australia.  “The White House did not have oversight of this process.  “There are mentions of a lot of high-profile names throughout this, and that’s not a surprise.”

title: ‘They’re angry’: Aussies abandon the major parties and turn to One Nation ‘grievance party’
description: Liberal Senator Jane Hume claims the Coalition hasn’t been giving Australians “what they want to hear”.  “Which is a genuine economic narrative and an alternative to this terrible Labor government that’s seen inflation go up, get it out of control, that potentially interest rates go up again tomorrow,” Ms Hume told Sky News Australia.  “They are feeling left behind. If we’re concerned about what we’re seeing in polls or what we’re hearing on the streets, well, that’s because Australians are aggrieved, and when Australians are aggrieved, they turn to a grievance party like One Nation, and that’s simply not good enough, and it’s certainly not sustainable.  “Unless the Coalition and it specifically the Liberal Party can turn around its message and deliver what Australians are looking for, which is a genuine alternative, well, then we deserve what we get.”

title: ‘Sussan Ley is our leader’: Liberal Senator denies there is a ‘challenge to the leadership’
description: Liberal Senator Jane Hume has denied that there is a challenge to the Liberal leadership.  This comes after Angus Taylor reportedly held talks with Andrew Hastie’s party room allies in a move to reunite the Liberal Party’s right faction ahead of a possible leadership spill.  “There is no challenge to the leadership. No one has put their hand up and said, ‘I would like to be leader, and I am challenging the current leader’,” Ms Hume told Sky News Australia.  “Sussan Ley is our leader, and we need to unite behind her and make sure that she has the support that she needs to present that credible alternative.”

title: ‘It’s sleezy, disgusting, creepy’: ‘Sinister’ new Andrew photos condemns him to ‘ignominy’
description: TalkTV host Mark Dolan claims things have gotten “worse” after the US Justice Department released over three million documents from the Jeffrey Epstein files.  These included some damning new images of Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor and private emails sent to Epstein.  There’s no suggestion of any wrongdoing, and Mr Mountbatten-Windsor has always denied allegations against him.  “This new photo is extraordinarily damaging to the Royal Family. And it means that Andrew’s brand – if it wasn’t already damaged – is over now,” Mr Dolan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “And the reason why is because it’s such a sinister photograph. Even if a crime hasn’t been committed, it’s a shocking look for the brother of the King of the United Kingdom.  “It’s creepy; it certainly raises more questions than it answers. There are really two photographs now that have condemned Prince Andrew or Andrew now to ignominy.  “It’s sleezy, it’s disgusting, it’s creepy.”

title: CNN forced to admit Melania documentary is a 'big success’ at the box office
description: CNN has been forced to report the Melania Trump documentary is a “big success.”  CNN host Brian Stelter said ‘Melania’ is now the number one documentary in terms of box office sales in about a decade.  According to studio estimates, the film debuted with a better-than-expected US$7 million in ticket sales.  It’s the best opening weekend for any documentary, outside of concert films, in 14 years.  US President Donald Trump labelled the Melania documentary “glamorous.”

title: Marjorie Taylor Greene defends arrest of Don Lemon in clash with Bill Maher
description: Former Representative Marjorie Taylor Greene has clashed with ‘Real Time’ host Bill Maher over the arrest of former CNN host Don Lemon.  Lemon was recently arrested and is now facing federal civil rights charges after attending a protest that disrupted a church service in Minnesota.  Lemon has argued that he attended the protest as a member of the press; however, MTG said she didn’t think it was “journalism”.  Maher had argued that it was “not good” to have Lemon arrested, prompting a response from Marjorie Taylor Greene.  Greene expressed that the federal law protects religious exercise at places of worship, accusing him of violating the “FACE Act”.

title: Massive interest rates Aussies could face if government spending growth remains
description: EQ Economics Managing Director Warren Hogan claims the RBA must reverse the three interest rate cuts it delivered last year before calling for lower public spending growth.  “We need the RBA to reverse the rate cuts of last year. They were a mistake, there's no two ways about it,” Mr Hogan told Sky News Australia.  “And then if they can get that done by May over the next three meetings, then the governments of Australia need to tighten up fiscal policy just a little bit.  “They just need to stop spending growing.”  He said federal and state governments did not need to cut “willfully and widely” to calm the economic pressures but called for the spending to be “restrained”.
